<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence on the future of the BBC</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Alan Morton [FBB0023]</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This submission is made by Alan Morton</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in a personal capacity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  I am</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a UK citizen,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> taxpayer and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">television licence payer.  Since the BBC is directly funded from taxes I consider that the views of citizens should be the main factor in determining the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">future of the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ummary of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">M</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ain </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oints:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A publicly funded broadcaster should provide a unique offering and not compete with commercial providers.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public funding should not provide an excuse or opportunity for ‘empire building’.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Overall the BBC’s outp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ut is no better or worse tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> that of commercial providers.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A publicly funded body should not leave itself open to allegations of political bias.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The purposes of the BBC as currently defined are too vague and wide ranging. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The purpose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> of public service br</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oadcasting should be narrowly focussed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Any operations funded by the public should satisfy the criteria of efficiency, effectiveness and economy.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The scope, scale and remit of a publicly funded broadcaster should </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">be </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the minimum necessary to meet its purpose.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Output and services should be determined on the basis of demand and demand should be measured by the willingness of viewers to pay for the service.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Programmes should be sought from those best able to provide h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">igh quality and good value for money. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Innovation should be left to the private sector.  The BBC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (if it is publicly funded)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should focus on high quality </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">programming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The licence fee (BBC Tax) is the most regressive and unfair form of taxation in the UK.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The compulsory BBC Tax should be abolished and the funding for the BBC should come through subscriptions for its services and / or advertising.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The requirement to provide ‘public service’ broadcasts should be a condition of the broadcast licence applied to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> all broadcasters in the UK.</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The basis on which free advertising for their products is given to celebrities by BBC executives should be examined by the National Audit Office. </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current method of governance of the BBC, involving the BBC Trust and Ofcom h</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as failed.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2.17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The lack of accountability and failure of governance would be overcome by adopting the funding mechanism outlined in paragraph 1</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is a wide </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">range </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">broadcast services </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">(entertainment, documentaries, childrens programmes, current affairs and news) </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">available to UK residents provided </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">variety of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">commercial </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">operators</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  There is no need to have a publicly funded broadcaster that </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">competes with priv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ate sectors providers.  It follows that if there is to be a publicly funded broadcaster its remit should be to make a unique offering, not duplicate that which is commercially available.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the extent of its offering should be limited.  Public f</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unding should not be used as an excuse</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or provide an opportunity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for ‘empire building’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, for example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by expanding into areas such as internet services</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and creating numerous television channels and radio stations.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How well has the BBC performed in the curr</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ent Charter period in achieving its mission and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">public purposes?</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s Royal Charter states that ‘The BBC exists to serve the public interest’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The BBC produces some excellent programmes in the fields of drama, documentaries and childrens entertainmen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t.  But its best programming is no better tha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the best programming provided by commercial operators.  The BBC also produces some appalling programmes which match the worst output from the private sector.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the field of news and current affairs there has been considerable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">justifiable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">criticism about political bias</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> across BBC programming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t is unsatisfactory that a publicly funded body should leave itself open to such a complaint</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and this is evidence of a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">failure of governance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 5pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Are the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public service broadcasting is any broadcasting service funded from taxes, but there is no universally accepted </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">model</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> for its scope and purpose.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The principle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> set down by Lord Reith </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">inform, educate and entertain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">"</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a useful starting point</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, but they come from a time when the BB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> was a monopoly provider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current Charter goes far beyond Lord R</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">eith’s simple principles and includes somewhat nebulous concepts </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in terms of broadcasting </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">such as ‘sustaining citizenship and civil society’, ‘stimulating creativity and cultural excellence’, ‘representing the UK, its nations, regions and communities’, and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ‘bringing the UK to the world and the world to the UK’.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">   The equally vague purpose of ‘helping to deliver to the public the benefit of emerging communications technologies and services’ seems to be a device for allowing the BBC to expend licence payers m</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">oney expanding its activities rather than concentrate on producing quality programming.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Furthermore</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> by expanding the definition of ‘public purposes’ in this way </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">it provides the justification for increased funding through the compulsory licence tax and th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e creation of what has proved to be an unmanageable monolith.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The purpose of public service broadcasting should be narrowly focussed and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, if it is to be provided by a publicly funded body, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> preclude involvement in activities which would directly compete or</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> duplicate private sector provision.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Furthermore the purpose</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> should be define</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in such a way as to allow objectives and targets to be set against which performance can be measured.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? </span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Any operations funded by the public should satisfy the criteria of efficiency, effectiveness and economy.  Public funding should not facilitate ‘empire building’ or </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">profligacy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Sadly,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it appears</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the BBC has failed to meet these criteria.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The scope, scale </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and remit of a publicly funded broadcaster should the minimum necessary to meet its purpose.  Taking the BBC as an example, it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> scope is too wide, its scale unmanageably large and its remit too extensive.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Should the BBC’s output and services be provided to</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 5pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Output and services should be determined on the basis of demand and demand should be measured by the willingness of viewers to pay for the service.  Public funding should not be expended to satisfy minority tastes. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What balance should be struck in what th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Value for money taking into account quality of output should be the main determining factor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in how programmes are commissioned</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Programmes should be sought from those best able to provide high quality and good value for money.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">What role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These activities should not be part of the remit of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a publicly</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> funded </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">BBC.  Innovation should be left to the private sector.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">If the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> BBC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is to continue to receive public funded its</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> focus </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">should be solely </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on high quality </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">programming</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">How should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The licence fee</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (BBC Tax)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is the most regre</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ssive and unfair form of taxation in the UK.  Whe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> law abiding families on the poverty line are force to choose between heating their homes and buying food they do not have the option of not paying the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">BBC Tax</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, even if they do not wish to avail of the serv</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ices provided by the BBC.  It must be particularly galling for them when they see BBC executive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> using L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ayers money</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to give their high paid friends si</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">x</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> figure pay-off</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in addition to their contractual entitlements.  Equally unpalatable is to find t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hat the BBC has been conniving with some of its most highly paid employees in tax avoidance measures.  Some of these high earning BBC employees probably get more in a month th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">an a L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ayer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on the minimum wage earns in a year.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It also seems bizarre </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that a body which is funded through a specific compulsory tax needs to spend some £5m a year on publicity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> department</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">!</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Should the quality of its output not speak for itself?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  No doubt in the run up to 2016 the BBC will expend a lot more public money trying</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to justify the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">status quo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current method of funding the BBC removes any incentive for the BBC to respond to public opinion either as regards programmes, ethics</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> or management.  It also appears to encourage profligacy within the senior management team</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who seem to regard public funds as their own private slush fund to use as they wish.  The BBC likes to present itself as a benevolent ‘Auntie’ wh</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o knows best for the children (L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ayers) and who to challenge would be discourteous and disrespectful.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I think a better analogy is a rapacious step-mother who</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">se</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> primary concerns are her own self-aggrandizement and self-interest,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> who intimidates and coerces the timid father (the BBC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rust) into compliance.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The solution to these problems is a new funding </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">approach</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for the BBC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">which</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> reflect</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> the existence of multiple providers within the UK.  New funding arrangements should be put in place for the BBC, obviating the need for public funding.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The compulsory BBC Tax should be abolished and the funding for the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">BBC should come through subscriptions for its services and / or advertising. The requirement to provide ‘public service’ broadcasts should be a condition of the broadcast licence applied to all broadcasters in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Parliament Channel should be fund</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed from direct taxation through the Home Office and any services provided to foreign countries in the UK national interest should also be funded by direct taxation through the Foreign Office. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It is a fallacy that there is no advertising on the BBC.  Almost every day, on programmes such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘Breakfast’, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘The One Show’,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the ‘Andrew Marr’ Sunday morning show</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ‘celebrities’ appear to advertise their products – books, record albums, films, concert</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> tours and stage plays.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This ‘celebrity’ clique is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> given a competitive advantage by advertising their products on prime time TV at no cost.  The basis on which this largesse is provided by BBC executives should be examined by the National Audit </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">O</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ffice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ho</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">w should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The current method of governance of the BBC, involving the BBC Trust and Ofcom has failed.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The evidence of this failure is easily illustrated:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Blue Peter debacle of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">2006</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">highlig</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">hted</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a culture of duplicity </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">within</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the BBC.  The all pervasive nature of this culture was acknowledged by the then Direct</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or General when he put in place, at licence payers expense, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a staff training course</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to ameliorate the problem</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Russell Brand / Jona</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">than Ross saga in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">200</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">8, together with the Saville </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">affair</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> suggests </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">degree of moral turpitude</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> within the management of the BBC.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The connivance between BBC management and its highly paid staff in tax avoidance activities (what the BB</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Trust likes to refer to as the ‘</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">freelancer arrangements’)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">severance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> pay arrangements whereby members of the senior ‘clique’ received payments outside the terms of their contracts amo</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unting to in excess of £25m of Licence P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ayers’ money.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  (</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It appears </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">that no one involved in this profligacy has suffered any sa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ction</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Indeed their arrogant performances at the PAC Hearings suggest no contrition, but then why should they feel any remorse, it was only Licence </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ayers money and it went to a good cause – thei</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r friends</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The contractual arrangements for </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">George Entwistle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and the severance payment of £450,000</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> which he received.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">19.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The BBC’s defamation of </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Lord McAlpine.</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The failure of governance is a consequence of a total lack of accountability.  In practical terms the BBC and the Trust are accountable to no one.  The </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">icence fee arrangements ensure that the BBC receives it funding no matter what it does.</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> BBC T</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rust </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">purports to rep</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">resent the interest of Licence P</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ayers</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, but Licence Payers have no role in the appointment of Trust Members and Trust Members are not in any way accountable to Licence Payers.  The Trust uses the ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">BBC’s Audience Councils’ as advisory bodies, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">but these are appointed by the Trust and are not accountable to Licence Payers.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The BBC Trust has</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as part of its role</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> ‘to protect the independence of the BBC’, and it often seems that the priority of the </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rust is to act as an advocate of the BBC rather t</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">han </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">safeguard Licence Payers interests</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Although Ofcom is supposed to have a role in gov</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erning broadcasters, through its C</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">odes of Practice, it appears that in the case of the BB</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> it has abrogated its responsibility in favour of the BBC and the Trust.  </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> effect the BBC ‘regulates’ itself, with disastrous results for Licence Payers and viewers.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This lack of accountability and failure of governance would be overcome by adopting the funding mechanism outlined in paragraph 1</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">6</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Such a system will make the BBC</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> accountable to its funders, whether they </span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> subscribers or advertisers.</span><span style="color:#333333; font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  Ofcom should then be required to fully accept its statutory responsibility and directly regulate broadcasters, including the BBC.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The broadcasting market has changed signifi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">cantly since the BBC was first established</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> With the wide range of providers now in the broadcast market a new model is required for the provision of ‘public service’ broadcasting and funding of the BBC.  The current system of a compulsory tax on all UK households to fund the BBC is both regressive</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and detrimental to the good management of the organization.  The BBC tax should be abolished and the BBC funded through subscription and / or advertising.  Such a system will resolve many of the governance failures evident in the current arrangements.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>